      </office:binary-data>
     </draw:image>
    </draw:frame><text:s/>(dove <text:span text:style-name="T1">h</text:span> è la stessa costante di Planck che compare nell’equazione si Schrödinger!); in questa visione l’intensità della luce è proporzionale al numero di fotoni che passano per unità di tempo moltiplicato per l’energia posseduta da ogni singolo fotone.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Secondo quest’interpretazione quando un fotone urta un elettrone gli trasferisce la sua energia; l’elettrone a questo punto può superare la barriera di potenziale che lo lega al metallo ed, una volta fuori, avrà un energia pari a quella fornitagli dal fotone <draw:frame draw:style-name="fr7" draw:name="Object19" text:anchor-type="as-char" svg:width="0.1866in" svg:height="0.1854in" draw:z-index="12"><draw:object>
      <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
       <semantics>
        <mrow>
         <mstyle mathsize="12pt">
          <mi mathvariant="italic">hν</mi>
         </mstyle>
         <mrow/>
        </mrow>
        <annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{hν} {}</annotation>
       </semantics>
      </math>
     </draw:object><draw:image>
      <office:binary-data>AQAJAAADrQAAAAIAFQAAAAAABQAAAAkCAAAAAAQAAAACAQEABQAAAAEC////AAQAAAAuARgA
       BQAAADECAQAAAAUAAAALAgAAAAAFAAAADALgAYACEgAAACYGDwAaAP////8AABAAAADA////
       1////0ACAAC3AQAACwAAACYGDwAMAE1hdGhUeXBlAAAwABAAAAD7AkD+AAAAAAAAkAEBAAAC
       BAIAEFN5bWJvbAACBAAAAC0BAAAIAAAAMgqAARkBAQAAAG4AFQAAAPsCQP4AAAAAAACQAQEA
       AAAEAgAQVGltZXMgTmV3IFJvbWFuAACDBAAAAC0BAQAEAAAA8AEAAAgAAAAyCoABOQABAAAA
       aAAKAAAAJgYPAAoA/////wEAAAAAABAAAAD7AhQACQAAAAAAvAIAAAAAAQICIlN5c3RlbQAA
       BAAAAC0BAAAEAAAA8AEBAAMAAAAAAA==
      </office:binary-data>
     </draw:image>
    </draw:frame><text:s/>meno quella che ha dovuto spendere per superare la barriera di potenziale <draw:frame draw:style-name="fr7" draw:name="Object20" text:anchor-type="as-char" svg:width="0.1417in" svg:height="0.1854in" draw:z-index="13"><draw:object>
      <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
       <semantics>
        <mrow>
         <mstyle mathsize="12pt">
          <mi>w</mi>
         </mstyle>
         <mrow/>
        </mrow>
        <annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{w} {}</annotation>
       </semantics>
      </math>
     </draw:object><draw:image>
      <office:binary-data>AQAJAAADjQAAAAIAFQAAAAAABQAAAAkCAAAAAAQAAAACAQEABQAAAAEC////AAQAAAAuARgA
       BQAAADECAQAAAAUAAAALAgAAAAAFAAAADAKAAaABEgAAACYGDwAaAP////8AABAAAADA////
       NwAAAGABAAC3AQAACwAAACYGDwAMAE1hdGhUeXBlAAAwABUAAAD7AkD+AAAAAAAAkAEBAAAA
       BAIAEFRpbWVzIE5ldyBSb21hbgAAgwQAAAAtAQAACAAAADIKIAFAAAEAAAB3AAoAAAAmBg8A
       CgD/////AQAAAAAAEAAAAPsCFAAJAAAAAAC8AgAAAAABAgIiU3lzdGVtAAAEAAAALQEBAAQA
       AADwAQAAAwAAAAAA
      </office:binary-data>
     </draw:image>
    </draw:frame>; dunque uscirà con un’energia <draw:frame draw:style-name="fr7" draw:name="Object21" text:anchor-type="as-char" svg:width="0.7681in" svg:height="0.222in" draw:z-index="14"><draw:object>
      <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
       <semantics>
        <mrow>
         <mstyle mathsize="12pt">
          <mrow>
           <msub>
            <mi>E</mi>
            <mstyle mathsize="8pt">
             <mi>e</mi>
            </mstyle>
           </msub>
           <mo stretchy="false">=</mo>
           <mrow>
            <mi mathvariant="italic">hν</mi>
            <mo stretchy="false">−</mo>
            <mi>w</mi>
           </mrow>
          </mrow>
         </mstyle>
         <mrow/>
        </mrow>
        <annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{E rSub { size 8{e} } =hν - w} {}</annotation>
       </semantics>
      </math>
     </draw:object><draw:image>
      <office:binary-data>AQAJAAADCgEAAAIAFQAAAAAABQAAAAkCAAAAAAQAAAACAQEABQAAAAEC////AAQAAAAuARgA
       BQAAADECAQAAAAUAAAALAgAAAAAFAAAADAJgAuAIEgAAACYGDwAaAP////8AABAAAADA////
       t////6AIAAAXAgAACwAAACYGDwAMAE1hdGhUeXBlAABgABUAAAD7AkD+AAAAAAAAkAEBAAAA
       BAIAEFRpbWVzIE5ldyBSb21hbgAAnQQAAAAtAQAACAAAADIKoAF+BwEAAAB3AAgAAAAyCqAB
       tgMBAAAAaAAIAAAAMgqgAUcAAQAAAEUAFQAAAPsCIP8AAAAAAACQAQEAAAAEAgAQVGltZXMg
       TmV3IFJvbWFuAACdBAAAAC0BAQAEAAAA8AEAAAgAAAAyChACYgEBAAAAZQAQAAAA+wJA/gAA
       AAAAAJABAAAAAgQCABBTeW1ib2wAAgQAAAAtAQAABAAAAPABAQAIAAAAMgqgAR8GAQAAAC0A
       CAAAADIKoAFeAgEAAAA9ABAAAAD7AkD+AAAAAAAAkAEBAAACBAIAEFN5bWJvbAACBAAAAC0B
       AQAEAAAA8AEAAAgAAAAyCqABlgQBAAAAbgAKAAAAJgYPAAoA/////wEAAAAAABAAAAD7AhQA
       CQAAAAAAvAIAAAAAAQICIlN5c3RlbQAABAAAAC0BAAAEAAAA8AEBAAMAAAAAAA==
      </office:binary-data>
     </draw:image>
    </draw:frame>. Questa formula è in perfetto accordo con i risultati sperimentali. Se per caso la frequenza della luce è troppo bassa e si ha <draw:frame draw:style-name="fr7" draw:name="Object22" text:anchor-type="as-char" svg:width="0.4272in" svg:height="0.1854in" draw:z-index="15"><draw:object>
      <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
       <semantics>
        <mrow>
         <mstyle mathsize="12pt">
          <mrow>
           <mi mathvariant="italic">hν</mi>
           <mo stretchy="false">&lt;</mo>
           <mi>w</mi>
          </mrow>
         </mstyle>
         <mrow/>
        </mrow>
        <annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{hν&lt;w} {}</annotation>
       </semantics>
      </math>
     </draw:object><draw:image>
      <office:binary-data>AQAJAAAD1QAAAAIAFQAAAAAABQAAAAkCAAAAAAQAAAACAQEABQAAAAEC////AAQAAAAuARgA
       BQAAADECAQAAAAUAAAALAgAAAAAFAAAADALgAWAFEgAAACYGDwAaAP////8AABAAAADA////
       1////yAFAAC3AQAACwAAACYGDwAMAE1hdGhUeXBlAAAwABUAAAD7AkD+AAAAAAAAkAEBAAAA
       BAIAEFRpbWVzIE5ldyBSb21hbgAAfgQAAAAtAQAACAAAADIKgAH6AwEAAAB3AAgAAAAyCoAB
       OQABAAAAaAAQAAAA+wJA/gAAAAAAAJABAAAAAgQCABBTeW1ib2wAAgQAAAAtAQEABAAAAPAB
       AAAIAAAAMgqAAZsCAQAAADwAEAAAAPsCQP4AAAAAAACQAQEAAAIEAgAQU3ltYm9sAAIEAAAA
       LQEAAAQAAADwAQEACAAAADIKgAEZAQEAAABuAAoAAAAmBg8ACgD/////AQAAAAAAEAAAAPsC
       FAAJAAAAAAC8AgAAAAABAgIiU3lzdGVtAAAEAAAALQEBAAQAAADwAQAAAwAAAAAA
      </office:binary-data>
     </draw:image>
    </draw:frame>, allora l’elettrone pur avendo ricevuto l’energia dal fotone non ne avrà a sufficienza per superare la barriera di potenziale, e quindi non potrà essere emesso.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Il fotone è una particella che corre alla velocità della luce, quindi per poterlo studiare bisogna usare delle equazioni che siano coerenti con la Teoria della Relatività.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">L’equazione di Schrödinger è stata formulata nella quarta scheda e l’abbiamo dedotta partendo dalla condizione che doveva essere coerente con l’equazione classica di Newton; ma questa equazione non è coerente con la Teoria della Relatività, quindi neanche l’equazione di Schrödinger è coerente con la la Teoria della Relatività. Dunque, purtroppo, l’equazione di Schrödinger non può essere applicata al fotone.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">In futuro studieremo la Meccanica Quantistica Relativistica, per ora, come risultato di questa scheda, ci ricorderemo della relazione di Einstein per l’energia dei fotoni <draw:frame draw:style-name="fr7" draw:name="Object23" text:anchor-type="as-char" svg:width="0.4465in" svg:height="0.1854in" draw:z-index="16"><draw:object>
      <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
       <semantics>
        <mrow>
         <mstyle mathsize="12pt">
          <mrow>
           <mi>E</mi>
           <mo stretchy="false">=</mo>
           <mi mathvariant="italic">hν</mi>
          </mrow>
         </mstyle>
         <mrow/>
        </mrow>
        <annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{E=hν} {}</annotation>
       </semantics>
      </math>
     </draw:object><draw:image>
      <office:binary-data>AQAJAAAD1QAAAAIAFQAAAAAABQAAAAkCAAAAAAQAAAACAQEABQAAAAEC////AAQAAAAuARgA
       BQAAADECAQAAAAUAAAALAgAAAAAFAAAADALgAWAFEgAAACYGDwAaAP////8AABAAAADA////
       1////yAFAAC3AQAACwAAACYGDwAMAE1hdGhUeXBlAAAwABAAAAD7AkD+AAAAAAAAkAEBAAAC
       BAIAEFN5bWJvbAACBAAAAC0BAAAIAAAAMgqAAQcEAQAAAG4AFQAAAPsCQP4AAAAAAACQAQEA
       AAAEAgAQVGltZXMgTmV3IFJvbWFuAADCBAAAAC0BAQAEAAAA8AEAAAgAAAAyCoABJwMBAAAA
       aAAIAAAAMgqAAUcAAQAAAEUAEAAAAPsCQP4AAAAAAACQAQAAAAIEAgAQU3ltYm9sAAIEAAAA
       LQEAAAQAAADwAQEACAAAADIKgAHQAQEAAAA9AAoAAAAmBg8ACgD/////AQAAAAAAEAAAAPsC
       FAAJAAAAAAC8AgAAAAABAgIiU3lzdGVtAAAEAAAALQEBAAQAAADwAQAAAwAAAAAA
      </office:binary-data>
     </draw:image>
    </draw:frame>.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Osservazione:</text:span> nella Teoria della Relatività per ogni particella si può calcolare l’energia e la quantità di moto secondo le formule <draw:frame draw:style-name="fr7" draw:name="Object24" text:anchor-type="as-char" svg:width="0.5472in" svg:height="0.211in" draw:z-index="17"><draw:object>
